{"type":"message","id":"5fe734b6","parentId":"d640550d","timestamp":"2026-05-16T04:43:19.257Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is that the file uses `export { createStory }` at the end, so it requires ES module mode, but Node ran it as CommonJS because of the inline argument. The `.mjs` extension would work, but the file is `.mjs` already... wait no, I named it `create_story.mjs` but saved it to `create_story.mjs` - let me check.\n\nActually, looking at the path in the error: `create_story.mjs` - yes it ends with `.mjs`. But the `export` statement at the end was causing the issue because Node should recognize `.mjs` as ES module. \n\nWait, the issue might be that I have both a CLI section AND an export at the end. Let me look at the script again. \n\nLooking at the file:\n```javascript\n// CLI\nconst args = process.argv.slice(2);\nif (args.length > 0) {\n  const title = args[0];\n  createStory({ title }).then(url => {\n    if (url) console.log('Done:', url);\n    else process.exit(1);\n  });\n} else {\n  // Export as module\n  export { createStory };\n}\n```\n\nThe `export` is inside an `else` block, which is invalid syntax. In ES modules, exports must be at the top level. Let me fix this.\n\nActually, the `.mjs` extension should make it an ES module, and the export statement is at line 180. But in JavaScript, you can't have `export` inside a block like `if/else`. The `export` must be at the module's top level.\n\nLet me fix the script by restructuring it:\n1. Always export createStory\n2. Have the CLI code check if it's being run directly","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_fSZDWWOAyYytQeRqbfOI7447","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\.openclaw\\workspace\\create_story.mjs","offset":165}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":455,"output":452,"cacheRead":118784,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":119691,"co